{
  "texts": [
    "After adjusting the q s value, a slight difference remains in the transition region (5-10 %) due to soft gluon contributions that were excluded by the q 0 cut.",
    "The value of q s which is obtained with q 0 ≃ 0 GeV can be treated as a pure intrinsic-k T and as shown in [1], it exhibits no pronaunced dependence on collision energy, √ s, neither on DY pair invariant mass..",
    "The determined value is 1.04 ± 0.08 GeV.",
    "It can be seen that the optimal value of q s for q 0 = 2.0 GeV is about twice as large as this one.As indicated in [3,4], the increase of the intrinsic-k T with increase of q 0 is related to the Sudakov form factor ∆(µ 2, µ 2 0) which gives the probability of no radiation between the two values of the scales, µ 0 and µ: Data q 0 ≃ 0 GeV, qs = 1.0 GeV q 0 = 1 GeV, qs = 1.4 GeV q 0 = 2 GeV, qs = 2.1 GeV TeV obtained with q 0 = 2.0 GeV using the optimal value of q s (red histogram) and the value of q s obtained for q 0 → 0 (blue histogram).",
    "The bands show the scale uncertainty.10 1 CMS, 13 TeV, Z/γ * → ℓ + ℓ -, 76 < m ℓℓ < 106 GeV dσ/dp T (ℓℓ) [pb/GeV] 1 10 1 0.5 0.6 0.7 0.8 0.9 1 1.1 1.2 1.3 1.4 p T (ℓℓ) [GeV] MC/Data q 0 = 2.0 GeV, qs = 2.1 GeV q 0 = 2.0 GeV, qs = 1.0 GeV 10 1 CMS, 13 TeV, Z/γ * → ℓ + ℓ -, 76 < m ℓℓ < 106 GeV dσ/dp T (ℓℓ) [pb/GeV] 1 10 1 0.6 0.8 1 1.2 1.4 1.6 1.8 2 2.2 p T (ℓℓ) [GeV] Ratio∆(µ 2, µ 2 0) = exp - b µ 2 µ 2 0 dq ′2 q ′2 z M 0 dz z P (R) ba (α s, z)(1)Here, z is the fraction of the longitudinal momentum transferred at the branching and P (R) ba is resovable splitting function which describes splitting of parton b to parton a [8,9]."
